<BR CLEAR=ALL>
<H3>THE TWO SIDES OF ORRIN HATCH<BR>
Strident Conservative or Thoughtful Moderate:<BR>
Which One Will Lead Senate Judiciary?</H3>

<H4>By Naftali Bendavid<BR>
Legal Times</H4>

<P>As the Senate clerk began the slow roll-call vote at 2:20 Thursday afternoon, Orrin Hatch thought he still had a minuscule chance to pull out a win on the balanced-budget amendment.</P>

<P>Sen. Mark Hatfield, the lone Republican opposing the amendment, might yet come around, Hatch thought, providing him the margin of victory. Just two hours earlier, Hatch and Sen. Paul Simon (D- Ill.) sat alone in the darkened Senate chamber, wondering if there was any way to swing Hatfield, and came up empty. But Hatch continued to hope.</P>

<P>Then the clerk called out "Mr. Hatfield." The Oregon senator responded "No" in a quiet, firm voice, and Hatch knew it was all over. He turned to staffers lined up against the back wall of the Senate chamber and shook their hands.</P>

<P>As he emerged into the elaborately tiled Capitol hallway, aide Sharon Prost startled the disconsolate Hatch with a hug. "Congratulations, boss," she said.</P>

<P>Others agreed. Sen. Larry Craig (R-Idaho) leaned through a cluster of reporters to shake Hatch's hand, saying, "You did a great job." Despite falling one vote short of the two-thirds majority needed, the countless hours of cajoling and speechifying only seemed to have increased Hatch's stature within GOP ranks.</P>

<P>Borrowing Vice President Albert Gore Jr.'s ornate Capitol office for an interview, the 6-foot-2, rod-thin Hatch looked uncharacteristically weary after 116 hours of floor debate.</P>

<P>"I've been through defeats before," he said resolutely. Then he confessed, "I'm absolutely exhausted." And, lowering his senatorial guard for a brief, plaintive moment, he added, "I just want to win."</P>

<P>The relentlessness that almost won Hatch a momentous victory last week has been a trademark during his 18-year Senate career. But it is all the more important now, because Hatch is suddenly a very powerful man.</P>

<P>In January, Hatch became chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee. And no one really knows what to expect.</P>

<P>Hatch's career, after all, has generated some grisly moments: Orrin Hatch calling the Democrats "the party of homosexuals" in a 1988 speech. Orrin Hatch in 1990 comparing Oliver North to Jesus Christ. Orrin Hatch waving a copy of The Exorcist in 1991 as he accuses Anita Hill of fabricating sexual harassment claims. Orrin Hatch, in the tone of a Sunday school teacher, killing a civil-rights bill or helping to smother the Equal Rights Amendment.</P>

<P>But there's another Hatch, too. No one dismisses him any longer as just a scorched-earth ideologue like Sen. Jesse Helms (R-N.C.). He helped push through a generous child-care bill in 1989, leading fellow conservatives to equate him with Karl Marx and Benedict Arnold. In 1990, he single-handedly saved a law forbidding discrimination against AIDS patients. An unusually considerate man, Hatch has forged a friendship with his political opposite, Sen. Edward Kennedy (D-Mass.), that has become legendary; Kennedy scrawled on a painting he gave Hatch in 1991, "We'll leave the light at the [Kennedy] compound on for you anytime."</P>

<P>A former trial lawyer now plying his advocacy skills in the Senate, Hatch, 60, has been mentioned as a potential Supreme Court justice in the past and doubtless will be mentioned again should President Clinton be ousted by a Republican in 1996. But in a sense, the Constitution is already on Hatch's desk. House Speaker Newt Gingrich is on a crusade to resurrect school prayer, weaken defendants' rights, limit politicians' terms, require a balanced budget. President Clinton is trying desperately to rebuff the onslaught. In many cases, the senator from Utah could tip the balance.</P>

<P>The question is: Which Orrin Hatch will it be?</P>

<P><B>Doing the Right Thing<B>
In a series of interviews in his elegant, slightly cluttered Senate office, Hatch struggles to describe himself, clearly uncomfortable with the attempt. His voice is low and controlled, as though to avoid expending any more energy than absolutely necessary.</P>

<P>"I'm motivated intensely to do what's right," Hatch says. "I really try hard. Sometimes, looking back on it, I didn't do what was right. Take Martin Luther King's holiday. I voted against that solely on the basis that I felt we didn't need another holiday. . . . And I was wrong. I was wrong. I didn't take into consideration how very important it was to a large segment of our population. If I had one vote I would cast again, it's that one."</P>

<P>The struggle embodied in that admission reflects a duality that has characterized Hatch's political life. In recent years, he has gained an increasing reputation for thoughtfulness, even moderation. But that only heightens the contrast with the harshness and stridency that have at times punctuated his career.</P>

<P>Spy magazine named Hatch to its list of the "100 Worst People and Events of 1992," tied for second with Sen. Alan Simpson (R-Wyo.) -- because, the magazine said, Hatch is an "evil GOP creep." In 1985, Eleanor Smeal, then president of the National Organization for Women, called Hatch a "fascist." In the early 1980s, Hatch's name was used in fund-raising letters -- by liberals counting on anti-Hatch sentiment.</P>

<P>There is something about Hatch that drives his opponents wild. "It's almost an aesthetic thing: He's prissy. He's too neat. He looks too much like a goody-two-shoes," says Eric Sterling, president of the Criminal Justice Policy Foundation, a generally liberal think tank. "If you wear cords or jeans and you have a beard, and maybe you're three weeks overdue for a haircut, you look at Orrin Hatch and say, 'Who's he trying to impress? He looks like the guy on top of the wedding cake.' "</P>

<P>Hatch, to be sure, has given liberal adversaries reason to resent him. From the day he walked through the Capitol doors in January 1977, having never before held political office, Hatch has combined an in-your-face sharpness in debate with a relentless legislative skill.</P>

<P>In a May 1978 battle that would set the tone for his career, Hatch commanded a tightly organized filibuster against a bill that would have given unions numerous new organizing tools. A little-known rookie senator, Hatch shocked the Senate's old hands with his instinctive strategic abilities.</P>

<P>Hatch focused on seven swing Democrats, he recalls, carefully tailoring his tactics to suit each senator. With Sen. Edward Zorinsky of Nebraska, for example, Hatch agreed, in return for Zorinsky's vote, to tell Zorinsky if the fight became hopeless, so Zorinsky could switch his vote and avoid the labor movement's wrath. As for John Sparkman of Alabama -- who, Hatch says, was elderly and vulnerable to persuasion -- Hatch assigned a senator to rush to Sparkman's side whenever a Democratic leader approached him.</P>

<P>Hatch worked 18 hours a day. He introduced roughly 1,200 amendments. In the end, he managed to torpedo legislation wanted badly by the entire labor movement, the Senate's Democratic leadership, and most of Hatch's colleagues.</P>

<P>"They weren't used to having Republicans stand up, especially some young senator from Utah," Hatch says of his colleagues. "But I'm not apologizing for it, because I believed in what I was doing."</P>

<P>In 1978, Hatch also began waging a furious battle against the popular Equal Rights Amendment. "I believe in equal rights for women," Hatch explains. "[But] we have over 20 laws that guarantee them. I would prefer to work with those 20 laws than write a 53-word definition into the Constitution that could be vastly misconstrued."</P>

<P><B>A Question of Style</B><BR>
Just a few years into his first term, Hatch was earning a reputation as a rigid right-winger, like Helms, only smarter and more dangerous. In 1982, he fought attempts to extend and strengthen the Voting Rights Act, a bill originally inspired by Martin Luther King Jr., and other civil-rights leaders. He thwarted for four years the "Grove City" bill --popular even with some Republicans -- which bans discrimination in colleges and other institutions receiving federal funds. Displaying a mastery of Senate rules, Hatch introduced some 1,000 amendments to that bill.</P>

<P>Hatch argues that affirmative action is merely discrimination in another form. "I want civil rights bills to be written right," he says. "I don't want them to be written where one group is pitted against another."</P>

<P>But to some, Hatch was an enemy, albeit a skilled one, who seemed to be everywhere at once. "Hatch is always there, even when it's above and beyond the call of duty," says Nan Aron, executive director of the Washington, D.C. -- based Alliance for Justice, which fights to put liberal judges on the bench. "Hatch is smart. He goes for the jugular. He knows exactly where to draw the knife and how to put it in."</P>

<P>It has often been Hatch's style, as much as his views, that upsets his adversaries. "Part of it is self-righteousness: 'I'm moral and [anyone] who disagrees with me isn't,' " says Elliot Mincberg, legal director of the liberal People for the American Way. "And part of it is that when he says things that aren't true, you're pretty sure he knows better. It's almost Orwellian, in that he'll insist that war is peace and lies are truth, and it's as though if you say it loudly enough and self -righteously enough, then it's true. That's infuriating."</P>

<P>Hatch concedes that some consider him harsh. But he attributes that to his first big fight, over the labor bill. "Because I had to take a very strong position, I got branded by some -- only by some -- as strident," Hatch says. "And I think some of that was deserved. Part of it was youthful excess and lack of knowledge. Part of it was lack of experience. Part of it was not knowing my colleagues as well as I should. All of which I've tried to overcome."</P>

<P>But it was not just the battle over the labor bill that earned Hatch some unflattering labels from liberals. At an October 1982 campaign debate at Brigham Young University, Hatch's Democratic opponent Ted Wilson recalls, Hatch equated opposition to Reaganomics with "socialism." When the crowd groaned -- even at conservative BYU that was considered a low blow -- Hatch glibly retorted, "Sorry if I've offended some Democrats."</P>

<P>In an August 1988 speech at a Utah Republican fund-raiser, Hatch, according to the Los Angeles Times, said Democrats "are the party of homosexuals. They are the party of abortion. They are the party that has fought school prayer every step of the way. They are the party that has basically, I think, denigrated a lot of the values that have made this country the greatest country in the world."</P>

<P>As recently as last summer's congressional debate over the 1994 crime bill, Hatch lambasted those opposing harsh mandatory sentences for drug dealers who sell to minors.</P>

<P>"I will never understand the liberal mind," Hatch declared on the Senate floor. "Why are they not more concerned about these kids?" (Hatch himself, in an article in the Wake Forest Law Review a year earlier, had acknowledged that there are numerous problems with mandatory sentences, and that they are often applied in an unfair way.)</P>

<P>None of this would matter much if Hatch were not so effective. Jesse Helms' statements may be more outrageous, but liberals find it easy to portray him as a buffoon, with his heavy jowls and antebellum oratory. Helms often seems happy to go down in flames for some arch-conservative principle. Not Hatch; he wants to win. And that makes him far more dangerous to the left.</P>

<P>"Once you determine that he will be your opponent, you'd better damn well be ready for a bloody battle," says Laura Murphy Lee, director of the American Civil Liberties Union's D.C. office. "He's dedicated, and he's focused, and he's thorough."</P>

<P>Wilson, the former Democratic Salt Lake City mayor who unsuccessfully challenged Hatch in 1982, recalls Hatch's dogged determination all too well. After a long day of campaigning in the tiny Utah town of Midway, Wilson relaxed at a home he owned nearby. He was surprised to get a call from Hatch who began telling him, "I really need your vote." Mystified at first, Wilson suddenly realized Hatch was merely calling local residents at random, and was not aware that he was speaking to his election opponent.</P>

<P>Wilson identified himself, and the two laughed. "But then I thought, 'I'm here putting my feet up, and he's on the phone. He's working harder than I am,' " Wilson recalls.</P>

<P>Hatch is notoriously persuasive when he takes a colleague aside for a sales job. "He just keeps coming," Sen. Simpson says. "He will drive you crazy. You'll tell him no, and he'll say, 'Come on now, you just go home to bed and think about how you've got to do this for your friend Orrin.' "</P>

<P>And Hatch can be blunt. "He very often will just get on the phone and say, 'This is Orrin. We've got a hearing this afternoon. How are you thinking of voting?' " recounts Randall Rader, a former Hatch aide and now a judge on the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit.</P>

<P><B>The Scrapper</B><BR>
Nothing brings out Hatch's aggressiveness like fights over judicial nominees. One of the great Republican crusades of the 1980s was a campaign to elevate shock troops of young conservatives to the federal bench. Liberals fought back, and the Senate Judiciary Committee became an arena for impassioned struggles over the nation's direction.</P>

<P>Hatch conducted hand-to-hand combat in the smallest of fights. In 1985, President Ronald Reagan nominated Joseph Rodriguez, a New Jersey public defender and a Democrat, to the New Jersey federal District Court. Hatch, along with Republican Sens. Jeremiah Denton of Alabama and John East of North Carolina, asked Rodriguez to fill out a special questionnaire that featured such loaded questions as "Do you believe that a 'viable' fetus is a human being?" Widely seen as bullying, the questionnaire provoked an outcry; the senators backed off, and Rodriguez was confirmed.</P>

<P>That skirmish, though, turned out to be merely a warm-up. In 1986 President Reagan nominated then Associate Justice William Rehnquist to be chief justice of the U.S. Supreme Court. The fight was instantly nasty, each side accusing the other of trying to shove its agenda down America's throat. Hatch was the Republicans' general, grilling witnesses, attacking liberals' motives, even inventing a term --"the Rehnquisition" -- to describe opponents' tactics.</P>

<P>Summing up on the Senate floor, Hatch thundered, "The inquisitors have searched in vain for any inconsistency, crack, or break that they might use to justify their foreordained verdict -- guilty, guilty, guilty."</P>

<P>With Hatch's help, Rehnquist was confirmed. Liberals were determined to do better when Robert Bork was nominated in 1987. They organized quickly, taking out full-page ads charging that Bork would dismantle civil rights, demolish a woman's right to abortion, and generally resurrect the social attitudes of the last century. Public sentiment veered against the judge.</P>

<P>Hatch fought back tenaciously. He had his staff circle and underline "flaws" in each anti-Bork ad. Throughout the hearings, Hatch periodically held up an ad, loudly voicing disgust at its errors. Hatch aide Rader, who helped find the "flaws," acknowledges that some of them were more substantive than others, but says there was pressure to find ever-greater numbers of mistakes.</P>

<P>The liberal groups so feared Hatch that they made an uncharacteristic decision not to appear before the Judiciary Committee. "Because of Senator Hatch's ability to dismantle the credibility and integrity of groups and make his opponents the issue, I suggested that groups not testify," says Kate Michelman, president of the National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League. "I think that was one of the most strategically important decisions contributing to the defeat of Robert Bork."</P>

<P>After Bork's ultimate rejection, Hatch was all the more determined to ensure the confirmation of Clarence Thomas in 1991. So when University of Oklahoma law Professor Anita Hill exploded on the scene with allegations that Thomas had sexually harassed her, Hatch and other Republicans struck back hard.</P>

<P>During Thomas's electrifying confirmation hearings, Hatch painstakingly took Thomas through each of Hill's allegations -- that Thomas had made lewd comments about a pubic hair on a Coca-Cola can, for example. But nothing approached the climactic moment when Hatch brandished a copy of William Blatty's novel, The Exorcist, and triumphantly quoted a passage in which a character refers to "an alien pubic hair floating around in my gin."</P>

<P>Hatch was convinced he had proved that Hill had fabricated her accusations. Hill's defenders were convinced Hatch was persecuting her. And much of the country was simply nauseated by the specter of a senator waving a copy of The Exorcist in defense of a Supreme Court nominee. "It was sleazy and slimy," asserts Rutgers University law Professor Frank Askin, a liberal judicial selection expert. "He made up things out of whole cloth to try to impugn her character."</P>

<P>Hatch defends his histrionics. "I said, 'There's something wrong here,' " Hatch says. "Did I like Anita Hill? Yes. Did I think she was a wonderful witness? Yes. Do I wish her well? You bet. But I believe Clarence Thomas."</P>

<P><B>Long Way from Pittsburgh</B><BR>
The anteroom to Hatch's office bristles with mementos: A photo of Steve Young, quarterback for the San Francisco 49ers, who, like Hatch, attended Brigham Young University. A medallion awarded by former Surgeon General C. Everett Koop. A political cartoon showing Ted Kennedy saying, "Remember, Orrin, we liberals are for the poor -- and we intend to keep them that way!"</P>

<P>In the office itself, six paintings are clustered on the wall, mostly landscapes by his favorite Utah painter, Veloy Eaton. Jewish paraphernalia -- skullcap, menorah, shofar -- are arrayed on a table behind his desk, testimony to Hatch's fascination with religion. (Hatch is a devout Mormon.)</P>

<P>This is a long way from Pittsburgh, where Hatch grew up dirt poor. His childhood home was built by his father out of used lumber, he recalls, and his first residence after he married his wife, Elaine, was a former chicken coop behind his parents' home.</P>

<P>Hatch's father trained him to be a lather, a metalwork construction tradesman, and he started at age 16. Years later, shortly after arriving in the Senate, Hatch remembers, he had a run-in with Robert Georgine, president of the AFL-CIO Building and Construction Trades Department. Hatch was considered virulently anti-union, and Georgine told him at a hearing, "The problem with you, Senator Hatch, is you don't know what it's like to work with your hands."</P>

<P>Hatch recounts, "And I leaned over and said, 'Bobby, do you realize I was a member of the Wood, Wire and Metal Lathers Union while you were president of the union?' I said, 'I could tie more lath with one arm tied behind my back than you could with both hands on your best day.' " Hatch guffaws. "I'm not sure he's ever liked me since."</P>

<P>Some speculate that Hatch's poor childhood is responsible for his tireless drive. "Orrin has crossed the economic and cultural spectrum of the United States," says Kevin McGuiness, a former Hatch aide and now a partner at D.C.'s McGuiness & Holch. "David Letterman sometimes says he's afraid someone will tap him on the shoulder and say, 'We didn't know you were here. Now go back to Indiana.' I think there's a little bit of that in Hatch."</P>

<P>Hatch, who has six children, attended Brigham Young University and the University of Pittsburgh School of Law, moving to Salt Lake City in 1969. He practiced various kinds of law, from defending alleged tax cheats to suing railroads on behalf on injured workers. Hatch spent 14 years developing the tactics he now uses daily in the Senate: endless preparation, aggressive attack on all fronts, timely use of devastating quips, direct assaults on his opponents' motives.</P>

<P>Walter Plumb III, Hatch's partner from 1974 to 1976, remembers visiting the courthouse to watch Hatch argue a federal tax-fraud case. "It was incredible," says Plumb, who still practices law in Salt Lake City. "Orrin dominated everything. Three women on the jury had tears running down their face. And he was defending a guy who hadn't filed his tax returns in five years!"</P>

<P>Hatch won five tax-fraud cases in a row, Plumb recalls: "It got to the point where I'd call the IRS and say, 'Send your best team from Washington. We're going to kick your butt.' "</P>

<P>Hatch says his courtroom experience has served him well, although he acknowledges such tactics can be overdone. "Sometimes, if you get too fierce and you get too combative, it can be a detriment to you," Hatch explains. "So you have to be careful that the skills that you've refined in courts of law and arguments of law don't become the sole arena for all you do. You have to temper those things with a respect for other people."</P>

<P><B>Missionary Zeal</B><BR>
While an impoverished childhood and a career as an aggressive lawyer have shaped Hatch, nothing has been as important as religion. The two cities where Orrin Hatch works, Washington and Salt Lake City, are both defined by powerful institutions -- one by government, the other by church. As Washington radiates outward from the Capitol, so Salt Lake City is centered on the Mormon Temple. Both cities number their streets based on their distance from the source of power; both are defined by their central shrine. Hatch moves easily between the two cities.</P>

<P>It is a cottage industry among Hatch-watchers to try to figure out just how his Mormonism affects him as a politician. Hatch is clearly a deeply religious man, yet he rarely mentions his faith in public.</P>

<P>"I'm not fanatic about it," Hatch says. "But each senator's total makeup comes from a complex variety of experience, and religion is one of the more profound and worthwhile of those sets of experiences."</P>

<P>Mormons believe that a small band of Israelites left the Middle East 600 years before the birth of Jesus and became the true heirs to the Christian church. Mormon doctrine -- with its belief that Jesus visited this continent and that some Native Americans are descendants of Israelites --  is a striking mix of Americanism and Christianity.</P>

<P>"Mormonism is a fascinating religion," says McGuiness, the former Hatch aide and a non-Mormon. "It's very specific. Unlike most religions, which are at times murky, if you have a question, they have an answer. I think that would bring you a confidence and [assurance] you wouldn't otherwise have."</P>

<P>Hatch's religious fervor showed up early, his mother, Helen, recalls: "He could stand up and recite Scriptures at a young age. He sang from three-years-old on -- country songs, church songs. 'The Old Rugged Cross' -- he sang that over and over. He memorized it."</P>

<P>Like other Mormons, Hatch served on a two-year mission after high school. His older brother Jess had died in World War II, and Hatch was determined to fill two missions, one for himself and one for his brother.</P>

<P>It is easy to see a missionary's zeal and moralism in some of Hatch's Senate speeches. And his Mormon beliefs -- with their emphasis on thrift, family, traditionalism -- mesh tightly with today's conservative movement. "It's deeper than politics; it's part of the culture," says Wilson, the former Salt Lake City mayor. "Mormons don't vote conservative because of specific issues. Conservatism is closer to the church, or closer to God."</P>

<P>Mormonism in Utah has become so entwined with Republicanism, says Wilson, a rare Mormon Democrat, that once when he was in church, someone joked, "What are you doing here? I thought you were a Democrat."</P>

<P>Hatch embodies this culture perfectly; he won a fourth term last November with 69 percent of the vote. Says Wilson, who now heads the Hinckley Institute of Politics at the University of Utah: "Hatch doesn't run around posing as Mr. Mormon, but he's been skilled at keeping a close-knit relationship with the church."</P>

<P><B>Personal-Freedom Fighter</B><BR>
It is not unusual for politicians to make purist speeches one day and gritty compromises the next. But Hatch's duality is on an entirely different level. Sometimes his sharpness and tactics approach those of heavy-handed Newt Gingrich. At other times, his eloquence in defense of AIDS patients and his courage on behalf of single mothers are positively moving.</P>

<P>Some compare Hatch to Jack Kemp, suggesting he fits with a new breed of conservatives who meld fiscal toughness with occasional social softness. But in truth the national political scene holds no one else like him.</P>

<P>To begin with, some liberals say he is more approachable than other hard-line conservatives. "He can be very thoughtful," says the ACLU's Lee. "At least you have a chance with him. With some members you don't even dare request an appointment."</P>

<P>Anthony Podesta, then president of People for the American Way, signed a fund-raising letter in the early 1980s featuring Sens. Hatch, Helms, and East as a sinister trinity. "It was about the heathens at the gate," Podesta says. "It was about how they were about to start running your life and invading your home and personal life."</P>

<P>Hatch anguished over the letter; he invited Podesta to his office and made the case that he is not an irredeemable opponent of civil liberties. Podesta, persuaded, dropped Hatch from the broadside. "We've managed to work together since then," says Podesta, who now runs Podesta Associates, a D.C. lobbying firm. "Helms and East were proud to be in our fund-raising letter. Hatch is a man of intelligence and integrity and was offended by what we said about him."</P>

<P>One of Hatch's more notable forays over partisan lines was in 1989, when he took on virtually the entire Republican Party in co- sponsoring a major child-care bill with Sen. Christopher Dodd (D- Conn.). The backlash was fierce. "I have been personally likened to Karl Marx, Benedict Arnold, and even Brutus," Hatch complained on the Senate floor just before the bill passed.</P>

<P>The most recent example of Hatch's standing up for a cause precious to liberals is his rescue of the Religious Freedom Restoration Act. To be sure, many conservative groups, including the Mormon Church, supported the bill. But when the legislation came under attack, it was from the right, and Hatch's response was critical.</P>

<P>The bill, overturning a recent Supreme Court decision, forbade the enforcement of state laws that interfere with religious practices unless the state has a compelling interest. But anti-abortion activists protested that it would allow women to claim a religious right to abortion. State attorneys general feared that prison inmates would demand steak-and-champagne dinners because some invented religion required it. Support grew for a series of exceptions to the bill.</P>

<P>Hatch insisted, publicly and vigorously, that if exemptions were allowed, the bill would unravel. That provided crucial cover for other conservatives, and the Senate passed the act unamended in October 1993.</P>

<P>Such defections have drawn criticism from Hatch's compatriots on the right. Thomas Jipping, who heads the Center for Law and Democracy at the conservative Free Congress Foundation, acknowledges that he does not always agree with Hatch's compromises. "He has a 'don't let the perfect be the enemy of the good' kind of legislative approach rather than a 'go for the gusto every time and let the chips fall where they may' style," Jipping says. "But as Senate Hatch likes to remind me, I wasn't elected to the Senate, he was."</P>

<P>The area where Hatch most consistently shows his gentler side is health. Hatch seems genuinely intrigued by medical issues. "He would borrow my medical textbooks," recalls F. Edwin Froelich, a physician and former aide to the Senate's Labor and Human Resources Committee, which Hatch chaired. "I know he read them, because he would call me with questions. I'd have to go and periodically clear my books off his bookshelves."</P>

<P>Hatch has been so approachable on health issues that some Democrats say they would rather work with him than someone like Sen. Nancy Kassebaum (R-Kan.). Kassebaum is more moderate but less flexible; Hatch is conservative, but willing to deal.</P>

<P>Take AIDS. The issue blew up in 1990 during debate on the Americans with Disabilities Act, a bill Hatch co-sponsored to guarantee equal rights for people with disabilities. With the ADA on the verge of passage, Helms proposed an explosive exception: Restaurants could remove food-handlers with AIDS. Helms apparently hoped this would split the ADA coalition. "The sole purpose of the amendment was to kill the ADA," asserts McGuiness, Hatch's former aide.</P>

<P>Pro-ADA activists asked Hatch to help fight the Helms proposal. After he determined that there was no public health justification for the Helms exception, Hatch quickly came up with a counterproposal that would allow restaurants to remove only food- handlers who develop diseases communicable through food; AIDS is not. Hatch's proposal would give cover to lawmakers skittish about openly supporting AIDS victims.</P>

<P>Tension built as the debate began. Clusters of lobbyists representing the disabled and restaurateurs huddled anxiously outside. After Hatch and others made a series of impassioned speeches, the Helms provision was defeated. The Senate then approved the ADA with a 91-6 vote. Outside the Senate cloakroom, an enraged Helms could be heard bellowing at Hatch, says Thomas Sheridan, a lobbyist for the ADA.</P>

<P>While Hatch says he does not condone homosexuality, he again locked horns with Helms when Helms repeatedly linked AIDS with homosexuality during discussion of a $600 million AIDS treatment bill Hatch co-sponsored in 1990. Hatch took the Senate floor for a breathtaking speech.</P>

<P>"I do not want to condemn to death any person who has AIDS in this country," Hatch told his colleagues. "I do not care, in all honesty, what it was that caused them to contract the disease. . . . I just want to help them. It is fair to say that AIDS is a flagrant, widespread epidemic of high-risk conduct in many of the people. But let me tell my colleagues, everybody in our society from time to time makes mistakes. Many people have emotional illnesses or mental diseases. Many people have not had the privileges that many of the rest of us have had. . . . Any of us who may stand by and criticize better look at ourselves. We better look into our own hearts and our own minds and our own lives and if anybody, even in this body, does that, they are going to have to conclude that there are a lot of things they can improve upon."</P>

<P>Hatch insists that his fight for causes like AIDS funding is in line with conservative ideology. "I think a true conservative has to be compassionate," he says. "Take somebody who is personally disabled and really can't help themselves. What kind of society would we have if it didn't lend a hand?"</P>

<P>Such views leave gay activists with mixed feelings about Hatch. "He's a cooperative conservative," concedes William Waybourn, executive director of the Gay and Lesbian Victory Fund. "He will never be a champion of what most of us understand as civil rights, but he does understand personal freedom."</P>

<P><B>Opposites Attract</B><BR>
Perhaps the best symbol of the softer Hatch is his friendship with Ted Kennedy. It is hard to imagine two more different characters than the freewheeling, liberal Catholic and the straight-laced, conservative Mormon. Kennedy was born rich; Hatch worked his way up from poverty. Kennedy's drinking has brought him trouble; Hatch's religion forbids drinking.</P>

<P>The relationship did not start well. "I came here to fight Kennedy," Hatch says. "I just felt like he exemplified everything that was wrong with America." He chuckles. "And to a large degree, I found out that he did. But I also found that there is a very good person there . . . who really sincerely wants to do well for people."</P>

<P>The turning point was Hatch's ascension to the chairmanship of the Labor and Human Resources Committee in 1981. Because of the committee's GOP contingent included several liberal members, Kennedy controlled the votes while Hatch controlled the chairmanship. Hatch faced a choice: scream at Kennedy and get nothing done, or work with him to churn out legislation. "I went to Ted and said, 'I've got to have your help,' " Hatch says. "And to his credit, he did help. And we became friends."</P>

<P>Moreover, they have become one of the most effective lawmaking combinations in history. Together Hatch and Kennedy have hashed out laws that limit employers' use of polygraphs, encourage development of drugs for rare diseases, and provide funding for job training. They also have teamed up to help pass a fair-housing law, the Americans with Disabilities Act, the Religious Freedom Restoration Act, drug and alcohol treatment programs, a series of AIDS grants, and numerous other bills.</P>

<P>When they join forces, they rarely lose. Hatch brings along so many conservatives, and Kennedy so many liberals, that a Hatch-Kennedy bill is almost assured passage.</P>

<P>"One of the things you learn on the Hill is that the Senate has about ninety-five talkers and five doers," says former Labor committee aide Froelich, now an associate at D.C.'s Shaw, Pittman, Potts & Trowbridge. "The vast majority of members haven't [pushed through] a single bill. They've just been there and cast votes. You learn at the staff level who the doers are. Orrin, everybody would agree, is among the small number of members who are doers. And Kennedy is, too."</P>

<P>They still disagree on most things, of course. While Hatch and Kennedy do not campaign against each other, in their own races each will pump up crowds by telling them he is needed in Washington to fight the other. Hatch and Kennedy will often bellow at each other, red-faced, at a Senate hearing, and soon afterward will be chuckling together -- like friends who go all-out in a football game, then share a beer.</P>

<P>Sometimes the two simultaneously agree on one issue and disagree on another. Two years ago, they differed sharply on the morality of fetal transplants -- Kennedy was for, Hatch against -- but were united passionately on the religious-freedom bill. "I remember Orrin and I were fighting hammer and tongs about fetal transplants, then we'd go and testify together on religious restoration," Kennedy says, laughing. "We would literally leave the floor together to testify, then come back again and go at it again."</P>

<P>The relationship goes beyond politics. In 1991, then Labor secretary Lynn Martin invited Hatch and Kennedy to her office, ostensibly to discuss policy. When Kennedy showed up with a huge valise, Hatch was mystified. It turned out the meeting was a setup for a surprise 57th birthday party for Hatch. Kennedy, an amateur artist, opened the valise and presented Hatch with a painting he had made of the Kennedy compound at Hyannisport, Massachusetts.</P>

<P>Kennedy is not the only opponent Hatch has charmed. Many of his political adversaries find that Hatch makes a point of being decent to them. "He's a very well-mannered, courteous, respectful gentleman whose every view I take the opposite side of," says former Rep. Don Edwards, a California Democrat.</P>

<P>Some, though, detect a whiff of unctuousness in Hatch's manner. Shaking hands with someone and telling them how much you respect them, then voting against everything they stand for may make you a decent person. It also may make you disingenuous, a good politician, or simply someone who wants to be liked.</P>

<P>Perhaps most startling, Hatch regularly tells his colleagues he loves them, according to his aides; that is not uncommon among Mormons, but few use the phrase so freely with outsiders. One aide recounts that the crusty Howard Metzenbaum, former Democratic senator from Ohio, once muttered after meeting with Hatch, "If Orrin tells me he loves me one more time, I'm going to kill him."</P>

<P>Wilson, Hatch's former election opponent, is struck by Hatch's desire to please. "My personal style is not to say to people, 'I'm voting against you, but I like you.' I'd feel like I was pandering. But [Hatch] does it naturally. He so wants to please people. He's the perfect politician."</P>

<P><B>Chairman Hatch</B><BR>
His skills as the perfect politician will, of course, be put to the test during his reign over the Judiciary Committee. The first session Hatch ran as chairman, a hearing on the balanced-budget amendment, began at 10 a.m. on Jan. 5. Kennedy, white hair falling over a red, rocky face, forced his bulk through the crowd and up to the dais. Sen. Simon stopped to chat with reporters in his familiar bass.</P>

<P>When Hatch arrived, he was clearly the star. Lobbyists and staffers, who had been milling in an indeterminate throng, jostled toward him. Impeccably dressed as always, with a swirling lava- red tie and a dark suit, he conferred briefly with Kennedy, dropped into his chair for the first time, he got the one in the middle and smacked his gavel down three times.</P>

<P>"I want to express my thanks to Senator Biden and his staff for all the help they've given us during this transition,'' Hatch said in his taut monotone, nodding toward former Chairman Joseph Biden Jr. (D-Del.) "I wish I could say it's my pleasure," Biden answered ruefully.</P>

<P>Still, the Hatch-run hearing proceeded amicably. The Democrats, after all, are used to dealing with Hatch. And despite Hatch's differing personas, certain distinct patterns underlie his approach, patterns that provide a hint as to what kind of chairman he will be.</P>

<P>Hatch compromises more easily in some areas than others, something that is likely to continue. While he and Kennedy have served together on both the Judiciary and Labor committees, virtually all their partnerships have come on labor-related subjects -- health, drug treatment, job training.</P>

<P>Hatch's background seems to push him toward a fierce, unyielding morality on questions of legality and wrongdoing; that, too, is unlikely to change. In Judiciary's realm of black and white, right and wrong, Hatch has typically found little room for compromise. He is inflexibly harsh on criminals. After all, you are either for the death penalty or against it. Social programs, however, permit more flexibility; if you want to spend $200 million on an inner-city program and your opponents want to spend $800 million, maybe something can be worked out.</P>

<P>"On social and people issues, I understand people have different points of view," says Hatch.</P>

<P>Hatch sees, and no doubt will continue to see, many issues as morality stories, with a victim and a villain. Clearly that is true of crime; he seems unwilling to concede that a defendant may have been victimized too. Affirmative action, he believes, oppresses non-minorities. He saw Robert Bork and Clarence Thomas -- but not Anita Hill -- as victims. On the other hand, when it comes to the disabled or AIDS sufferers, he sees that they are victims too. And when he has been persuaded that the poor are victims, he has supported programs like child care and job training.</P>

<P>Hatch dislikes being labeled anti-feminist, anti-civil rights, or even anti-government, in contrast to many conservatives who could not care less, or even wear those labels with pride. "There are some conservatives who think that government is totally bad," Hatch says. "Well, that's just not true. There is a need for government. There is a need to have rules and regulations. But they ought to be reasonable."</P>

<P>And Hatch says he has mellowed over the years. "I'm still the same person," he says. "I still believe very strongly in what I do. . . . But experience does teach you to be a little more sophisticated, a little more personable."</P>

<P>Even Metzenbaum, the old liberal warrior whose office was across from Hatch's in the Russell Senate Office Building, grudgingly concedes Hatch has changed. "Generally speaking, Orrin is an able senator," Metzenbaum says. "He has become just a wee bit more moderate as his tenure in the Senate has extended."</P>

<P>Hatch has developed cordial relations not only with congressional Democrats, but with the Clinton administration as well. "It's been terrific to work with him," says Assistant Attorney General Eleanor Acheson, who coordinates the administration's judge-picking. "He has been very direct and straightforward to deal with."</P>

<P>As Washington enters a contentious two years, those good relations are likely to thrust him often into a mediating role between Gingrich Republicans and Clinton Democrats. "I'm not nearly so partisan today as I was when I came here," Hatch says. "I came here thinking I'm going to stop these Democrats. Today, I decry the partisanship. I'd like to see us work better together."</P>

<P>Thus far into the Republican onslaught, Hatch has taken moderately conservative positions. He pushed hard for the balanced-budget amendment and a line-item veto, for example, but did not support a requirement that Congress approve tax increases with a three-fifths majority. Hatch favors a school-prayer amendment, but one that would allow only silent reflection, not vocal worship. He has spoken in favor of limiting -- but not capping -- punitive-damage awards in civil cases. And he flat-out opposes imposing term limits on members of Congress. On crime, though, Hatch has co-sponsored a bill to make last year's draconian crime law harsher still.</P>

<P>Hatch also faces a task less concrete than churning through legislation: restoring the reputation of a Judiciary Committee whose public image still has not recovered from the debacle of the Clarence Thomas hearings.</P>

<P>Whatever Hatch does, it will at least be interesting. Dozens of bland figures pass through the Senate. Hatch is not one of them. "You can't throw Orrin into one category," says former aide McGuiness. "If you wrote a political novel, you'd have to have a character like Orrin in it. Otherwise it would be too boring."</P>

<P>(Legal Times is an affiliate publication of Court TV.)
Copyright 1995, American Lawyer Media.</P>
