<P><B>LEGAL TIMES SEPTEMBER 4, 1995</B></P>

<P><B>INTERVIEW</B> </P>

<P><B>Reed Hundt Picks His Battles</B> </P>

<P>Juggling the deregulatory zeal of the Republican-dominated 104th Congress and the ongoing, massive convergence of telecommunications technologies and companies, Reed Hundt, chairman of the Federal Communications Commission, faces an unusual balancing act. </P>

<P>With influential Washington think tanks such as the Progress & Freedom Foundation clamoring for the agency's abolition, Hundt has the unenviable task of explaining why federal regulation of the industry is still necessary. </P>

<P>At the same time, he and his agency stand as referee in a clash of the telecom titans, a clash that has already begun but will undoubtedly accelerate if and when far-reaching telecommunications reform legislation, passed by both the Senate and the House of Representatives, gets the final nod from Congress and President Bill Clinton. </P>

<P>In an interview with Legal Times, Hundt, a boyhood friend of Vice President Albert Gore Jr. and a former partner in the D.C. office of Los Angeles' Latham & Watkins, spoke out about the continued need for the FCC as a guardian of the public interest and a champion of competition in the communications sector. Critical both of traditional regulatory models and of conservative plans to wipe out or radically scale back the FCC, Hundt bemoaned the years of neglect that have left the agency's public interest mandate badly in need of resuscitation. And he proposed making the public interest a central organizing principle of a new, more streamlined commission. </P>

<P>From his spacious but modestly decorated eighth floor offices at the FCC's M Street headquarters in Northwest Washington, Hundt also described the FCC's unfortunate history of being held captive to the businesses it regulates. He decried 10 years of delays in telecommunications reform legislation. He trumpeted commission plans to force broadcasters to increase educational programming and ensure that the new generation of digital television includes educational broadcasting. And he came down against the proposal by Sen. J. James Exon (D-Neb.) to restrict obscenity on the Internet, endorsing instead a House -passed amendment, sponsored by Reps. Christopher Cox (R-Calif.) and Ron Wyden (D-Ore.)_that explicitly denies the FCC any jurisdiction over online content. </P>

<P>But on one of the most pressing topics of the day, giant media mergers and the FCC's role in policing them, Hundt was conspicuously silent. A spokesman responding to a follow-up request to discuss the subject said Hundt would not comment on the recent spate of mergers because even a general statement could be seen to "prejudge any of the matters that might be submitted for approval." </P>

<P>What follows are excerpts from the Aug. 29 interview, which was conducted by Reporter Benjamin Wittes. </P>

<P>Legal Times: If you had to identify the things that you've done here that you're most proud of and the things that are most urgent that you would like to do, what would they be? </P>

<P>Hundt: There's three things. First of all, we need to clarify what it means to talk about the public interest in telecommunications. We need to define it with specificity, meaning that we have to make sure that advocating the public interest is not some grand hoax that we perpetrate on the American public or a kind of secret do-si-do dance that we do with business. We need to make sure that it generates deliverables_real services and products that serve the public. </P>

<P>The second thing is that we need to not only talk the competition talk but we need to walk the competition walk_meaning that we need to apply sound antitrust principles to all of our analysis, use economics, and come up with policy conclusions that further a real competition model. That's why we needed to kill prime-time access rules [under which network affiliates had to carry minimum quantities of nonnetwork programming during prime time]. That was totally inconsistent with any concept of fair, evenhanded competition. </P>

<P>That's why we needed to auction [off spectrum for] PCS [personal communications systems] . . . so that we would have at least five or seven different competitors in global communications. </P>

<P>Historically, the commission would have just picked one or two winners. . . . It would have tilted in favor of one business at the expense of another. It would have done this at the behest of well-heeled lawyers and lobbyists who are constantly packing our hallways here. It's time to get rid of the old regime of picking winners and playing favorites and rewarding friends, and get to the pure competition model. </P>

<P>And the third thing we have to do is trim down the agency. We have to get smarter with communications technology. We have to be open to the public, such as on the Internet. We have to reallocate our resources in an era of shrinking resources. We have to close offices where automation can replace people. We need to take the pain that goes with that. We need to beef up our economists and lawyers and accountants and statisticians and industry analysis, so that we understand what we're doing on our policy issues. That requires a lot of change in the organization. It's long overdue. It's very painful. It's not enjoyable to have [reductions in force], but it's past time to do this. </P>

<P>Legal Times: [I]n the past six months, it has repeatedly come up in public policy forums whether there should even be an FCC. A number of public policy organizations and congressional conservatives have suggested either eliminating the agency or radically scaling it back. At a time when everybody accepts the premise of increased competition, what is the role of a federal regulatory agency in the telecommunications field? </P>

<P>Hundt: Our No. 1 role is that we are the principal advocate of the public interest in the communications sector. If you think that the public property of the airwaves should be used for any public purpose, you need to have a public agency and an advocate of the public press for that purpose. That's the FCC. </P>

<P>If you believe, as the inaptly named Progress & Freedom Foundation believes, that there is no public use that's appropriate for the airwaves, that you ought to totally privatize the airwaves, then it follows that you don't need any FCC to be dedicated to that mission. If that's your philosophy, you probably believe we ought to privatize the Grand Canyon; you probably believe that we ought to have no government whatsoever; you probably think that we ought to get rid of the Department of Education and give everybody a voucher so that they can create home schools or charter schools. That's a philosophy, but it's not what most Americans want, and it's not what Congress has asked us to do. </P>

<P>Number two, only complete ignorance of the history of business and antitrust law could cause anyone to believe that simply stating that you want competition is the way you get competition. Saying that you're for competition means that you then have to commit an agency of the communications sector_or some other agency of some other sector_to actually drafting and implementing the blueprint for how you get to competition. </P>

<P>Because we don't have a lot of competition in communications right now. We're not writing on a blank slate. We're talking about introducing competition in markets that are dominated by well-muscled, heavily larded monopolies. They need to be subjected to fair rules of competition so that new entries have a chance. </P>

<P>Now let me just say, there are people who fool themselves into believing that the communications sector is so inherently dynamic that no rules whatsoever will give you fair competition. But nobody in the business thinks that. I do think that legislative and administrative delays in progress to competition are inexcusable. </P>

<P>Legal Times: Are you referring now to the telecommunications bill? </P>

<P>Hundt: I'm referring to the last 10 years of efforts in Congress to try to get a law . . . [and] efforts at the FCC to try to promote competition. We have to recognize that we need no-excuses regulation, meaning that the regulators should provide no excuses for the business people. What we should provide are a set of fair rules of competition. </P>

<P>Legal Times: I want to go back to your point about the public interest. One of the comments that [former FCC official] Peter Pitsch [who helped prepare the Progress & Freedom Foundation's report] made was that he really didn't believe in the public interest. . . . He thought that the term was so vague as to be meaningless. </P>

<P>Hundt: Peter Pitsch helped make it vague. Peter Pitsch was here at the FCC when the public interest was gutted of all meaning and the law was distorted into a play on words, in which my friend and former colleague, [former FCC Chairman] Mark Fowler said, "The public interest isn't anything other than whatever interests the public." And then he went on to suggest that if the public watches what's on TV, then that demonstrates that what's on TV is in the public interest. It's a circularity that was elevated by the FCC to a principle of law and regulatory philosophy. But I don't agree with that, and I don't think that's the law. </P>

<P>This is a principal difference between me and those administrations. My view is that the problem with the phrase, public interest, convenience, and necessity, [from] the 1934 Communications Act is not that it inevitably has no meaning, but rather that for 60 years, the commission has done everything it can to strip that phrase of all the potential meaning that it could have. </P>

<P>Legal Times: In a concrete way, what is the potential meaning that it could have? What are some real-world examples of the FCC protecting the public interest? </P>

<P>Hundt: A real-world example could be that we would say to all people who hold on a temporary basis_for free_broadcast TV licenses the following: In order to keep this license, you must deliver five hours of children's educational TV in each market per week. You don't have to show all of it yourself; you can find someone else who will carry some of it_make some of it tradable. That way [for-profit broadcasters] would help fund [the Public Broadcasting Service]. We don't want to worry about the definition [of educational programming]. We're willing to accept the industry's suggested definition, which happens to be extant right now. . . . </P>

<P>It's very workable. We're willing to have you be held accountable by your local communities as to your performance toward that definition, and let the complaint process generate whatever objections there are. We're willing to let you teach on educational TV anything you want_creationism or evolution_the government won't get involved. We won't say anything about the substance; you'll have complete First Amendment rights as to what you utter. But you will deliver this product in concrete, specific, real amounts to parents and children in your market. And furthermore, we could tell them quite reasonably to tell parents when the shows are, so you can find it in the TV guide, which you cannot do now in the avalanche of entertainment and infotainment that you receive over the air. </P>

<P>Now if we did this, it is just a plain fact that millions of American homes and tens of millions of American children would get something they don't now get. I'm not saying it necessarily would be as popular as "Seinfeld." That's not the point. The point is not that broadcasters should get as rich as they possibly can on each and every half hour, but rather that if you believe in the public interest, in fair, concrete, manageable obligations, it's a perfectly reasonable way to go for the country. </P>

<P>Legal Times: Where are the children's television_the educational television_rules now? </P>

<P>Hundt: Comments are going to be due in the middle of October, reply comments in the middle of November. . . . Congress underscored the importance of children's educational and informational programming by passing a whole separate law in 1990. . . . </P>

<P>It's right and proper to continue to examine here at the FCC what should constitute a public interest obligation. It could and should be an evolving concept. </P>

<P>Instead, it has devolved into absolute meaninglessness in two respects: First, the FCC has presided, over the last 15 to 20 years, in gutting any sense of obligation. So the broadcasters out there feel_with some justice_that the FCC will never ask them, as the rules now stand, to deliver any public interest programming_or at least [will] not care if they fail to do it. The proof of that is that in the last 15 years, the total number of TV licenses that have been lost in proceedings at the FCC because of a failure to meet the public interest obligation is zero. </P>

<P>Legal Times: Should that number go up? </P>

<P>Hundt: Well, let me put it this way: Intuitively, it's pretty hard for anyone to believe that the reason it's zero is because TV has gotten better at delivering public interest programming over the last 15 years. The reason it has gone to zero is because the FCC adopted the philosophy that I earlier talked about that basically said in transparent terms_and I think in terms inconsistent with the 1934 Communications Act and the Children's Television Act_the FCC basically said, "Do anything you like, and we'll bless it." Well, that's the first reason that the public interest obligation has become, in effect, in legal terms, a sad joke. </P>

<P>The second reason why this obligation has failed to develop as it should have into concrete, real, specific deliverables to the American people, is that before an era of gutting the standard of any possibility of enforcement, the FCC was too content with a broad, vague, ambiguous standard. </P>

<P>This takes you back to a different philosophy . . . or the notion that the FCC chairman would be the national nanny or the occupant of a bully pulpit. That's the notion that there's some vague public interest standard, and the chairman of the FCC or the commission as a whole will let you know what it is from time to time. And you better watch out because if they raise their eyebrows or if they're a little unhappy, you better mend your ways_mend your programming and mend your ways. </P>

<P>Well, that concept, number one, was doomed not to work because it fundamentally rested on a concept of bluffing_as in poker_where the FCC would never, in fact, deal itself any cards. Because you never would, in fact, enforce anything. Secondly, that concept, that philosophy, I think we can now see in retrospect, was antithetical to any notion of First Amendment values. Nothing could be more chilling for freedom of speech for broadcasters than having an FCC that threatened to punish them by the death penalty of taking away their licenses but without saying how, when, or why the death penalty would ever be meted out. </P>

<P>Legal Times: At the same time as there have been calls for radical reform of the agency, the House and Senate have both passed bills that seem to invest a lot of authority in the agency in terms of managing the transition to competition. It seems to me like there's a bit of doubletalk there. On the one hand they say this is an overzealous regulatory agency, on the other hand [they say] let's give it the following new responsibilities. I'm wondering whether that has caused problems for you guys in terms of planning and trying to figure out what you're going to look like in the next few years. </P>

<P>Hundt: I think it's important to pick out from the not always harmonious voices of congressional views a couple of main themes and listen to them. </P>

<P>First, Congress is saying, in a variety of different ways, "FCC, we want you to really commit to competition from here on out. We don't want you to just talk about it but to cut special deals for favorite parties and delay proceedings that would permit people to enter markets. We want you to be real about it." </P>

<P>I think we should listen to that; I think we should adhere to that. That's why I believe so strongly that we should simplify licenses_the process of getting licenses to use the spectrum_by going to auctions wherever and whenever possible. </P>

<P>Now, I have been arguing with a couple of my colleagues here, who have opposed me on a couple of auction proceedings. But I think that auctions are in sync with what Congress is telling us to do generally about aggressively moving to competition. And I'm going to keep arguing for auctions. </P>

<P>Second, Congress is saying to us, "We want you to be as lean, efficient, and open to the American public as you possibly can be." I'm totally in agreement with that. I'm the first chairman to have a computer; I'm the first to send an e-mail. One of the happiest moments of my life was when I was able to announce that we'd gotten everybody at the FCC on the information highway. Instead of being shamefully out of touch with the very technologies that we're supposed to be talking about, working on, we at last are using them. </P>

<P>That's why we have to continue to close offices. And a couple of my colleagues disagree with me on this, but they're entitled to disagree. . . . </P>

<P>The third thing that Congress is saying to us is "Trust in markets; use economics. Trust in markets; they're going to work out." I'm totally in agreement. That is one of the reasons I've doubled the number of economists here. Not because I want them to spend their time counting beans and pushing columns of numbers left and right, but because I want them to advocate internally on each and every policy issue the view that economics is a sound discipline, that if you trust in markets, you're going to maximize consumer welfare, and efficiency gains are going to be tremendous. And on that subject, little by little, I think we're seeing a sea change in the agency's approach. </P>

<P>So I think a lot of the things_maybe the bulk of the things_that are being said in Congress today, I'm happy to be implementing. </P>

<P>There is one point of difference. There are people in Congress . . . who assert that there simply isn't any public interest in the communications sector. There we differ. . . . </P>

<P>Legal Times: I understand that the House bill and Senate bill are very different. But by and large, are you comfortable with the direction that the bills are going? </P>

<P>Hundt: Well, I think everyone on both sides of the aisle and people in the White House are very comfortable with the fundamental precept of the Senate bill and the House bill in this Congress_and with the Senate bill and the House bill in the previous Congress_which is that we should lower the barriers that prohibit entry of firms into other markets. There's really no question about that. </P>

<P>Second, there are a number of ways in which the Senate and House bills today do memorialize a commitment to the public interest, and I think everyone's comfortable with that. But there are also a number of major issues on which there is major disagreement_and on those issues, I think it's right for the FCC to not take sides but to wait and to commit to perform faithfully all the duties that Congress decides to give us, assuming that a bill does become law. </P>

<P>Legal Times: Have you made your views known on those specific issues to the administration? </P>

<P>Hundt: Let me put it this way: We have offered, in most cases quietly, our technical expertise to anybody_Republican or Democrat_who wants it. And we're still doing that. But nobody wants us to enlist on one side or the other of the partisan fights. We're not doing that. </P>

<P>Legal Times: On one specific matter, though, the two bills have a profoundly different view of the FCC's jurisdiction over content on the Internet. From the Exon bill in the Senate to the Cox/Wyden bill in the House, it runs, I think, about the gamut. </P>

<P>Hundt: Right. Well, on that one I have violated the self -imposed rule that I mentioned to you. And I have said that I personally_speaking very personally_I favor the Cox/Wyden approach. </P>

<P>Legal Times: You don't think that the FCC should have any jurisdiction over content, which is really what it says, right? </P>

<P>Hundt: No, I think that the Internet is a curious, strange, and incredibly important phenomenon. It does have dangerous implications. It also has numerous positive implications. But the Cox/Wyden approach would permit the country to cope with the downside. </P>

<P>Legal Times: [But] a lot of the things you said previously about the public interest with respect to educational television imply that in the broadcast media, the FCC ought to have a role in talking about content. . . . But why the discrepancy: no content regulation on the Internet but a role for the FCC in broadcasting? </P>

<P>Hundt: It's not about content; it's about the public interest. It's in the public interest to have a free over-the -air medium that delivers children educational TV, that provides a forum for political debate. We would be much healthier as a country . . . if political debates directed toward electing candidates could be conducted via broadcast and if candidates didn't have to pay for the time. We'd be much healthier as a country. </P>

<P>But when you turn to the Internet, I think the public interest goal is a different one. I think it is that there ought to be Internet access for every kid in every classroom and for every teacher in the country. And I think that the FCC ought to have that as a chief mission. I think we ought to accomplish that. I think as long as we're not focused on that, we're running the danger that the Internet will become the dividing line between the haves and the have-nots in our country. </P>

<P>Legal Times: What's the regulatory vehicle for ensuring access? </P>

<P>Hundt: Basically, I think we ought to use each and every tool we can find. For example, I think that telephone companies ought to be given incentives to provide Internet access. Cable companies ought to be given incentives to provide Internet access. I think that any tool we can find to get this done is a good one. Obviously, I prefer efficient market-based techniques. I prefer technology-neutral techniques. . . . </P>

<P>I think [universal Internet access] would revolutionize education. It could not possibly fail to achieve numerous successes, and the examples are already starting to pop up_test models that have already been run. Santa Clara, in California, has done this in a couple of schools; test scores go through the roof. Union City, New Jersey-Bell Atlantic test, scores are going through the roof. . . . There's only a handful of tests all over the country. But scores go right through the roof, class participation goes up, attendance goes up, dropout rate goes down. . . . </P>

<P>Legal Times: When you say incentives to provide access, are you talking about spectrum allocation? </P>

<P>Hundt: Well, we just signed Time Warner in something called the social contract (Legal Times is a Time Warner affiliate). The deal had many parts, but they lowered the price of basic cable; they agreed to provide connections to classrooms at cost; and they, in turn, are getting greater flexibility on price for enhanced basic. They're happy with the deal; we're happy with the deal. . . . We are working on similar ideas with other cable companies. That's an example, and there are other examples that you will see over the next three months. </P>

<P>Legal Times: I always hear about [high-definition television] and video dial tone, and sometimes I hear about them as examples of great opportunity for the FCC, and frequently I hear about them as FCC foul-ups over the last few years. I'm wondering if you can address them specifically. Was it a mistake to give away all the spectrum on HDTV? </P>

<P>Hundt: Well, we haven't given away any of the spectrum yet. The digital TV spectrum is the spectrum that lies in the gaps right now. In Washington, D.C., you have Channel 4, Channel 5, and Channel 7. The digital spectrum is in what would be Channel 6. It lies in the gaps; it can't be used now by analog broadcasters because of interference, but if they used digital technology, they could use it. By November of this year, the digital technology will be fully tested, complete, ready to roll after about a seven-year process conducted by a consortium of industries called the Grand Alliance. It's a fantastic technology. It can take one TV channel_6 megahertz_and get four or five signals out of it or one high-definition signal and maybe one other signal. </P>

<P>In other words, there's all kinds of flexibility available in terms of what can be transmitted digitally. </P>

<P>In the middle of October, we are expecting comments on our proposal, which is: Given the law the way it is written, shouldn't we give the digital spectrum to broadcasters for free, and shouldn't they, in return, make two promises to the American people? First, that they will, over time, return the analog spectrum and shut down the analog system, and second, that they will perform a variety of public interest obligations. </P>

<P>That's our proposal, given that the law precludes us from auctioning the spectrum. </P>

<P>Legal Times: And the law precludes that because . . . ? </P>

<P>Hundt: Because we're not permitted by law to auction any spectrum that's used for broadcast_free over-the-air broadcast. So Congress could change that law as part of the budget process, but that's not our issue. We'll do what Congress tells us. If they don't want it auctioned, we won't auction it. </P>

<P>But the important thing here is whether digital TV is going to be as good and bad as analog TV is_that is, as positive a force and also as mixed a blessing as analog TV is. Or do we have a chance to set up a system that is likely to maximize public interest benefits of free over-the-air television? And the fact is that we have a second chance to get this right, and the FCC is building on a history of failure and playing favorites and being overwhelmed by special pleading and intimidated by political pressure. </P>

<P>So we don't have a very good track record to suggest that we can get this right. But I believe that this commission has in it commissioners and able people on the staff who will get this right. And furthermore, we are very much more likely to get this right if the American people know what's going on, and there's an alertness to the fact that we're going to be defining in the next year the history of TV in the 21st century. </P>

<P>Legal Times: If one of the premises of all of this is that you're having a convergence of technology because all digital media is essentially the same, the FCC is still divided into six bureaus that are organized along traditional broadcast lines, I'm wondering, can we expect an internal reform of the bureau system to parallel . . . the convergence of the technologies? </P>

<P>Hundt: Well, in some out year, it's probably right for the FCC to be organized by functions instead of by industry, namely enforcement, licensing, and policy. However, that kind of organization, that kind of change in an organization is incredibly disruptive and incredibly time-consuming. And that is just going to have to wait for an out year. I don't know when because, frankly, we don't have the time to spare to make that kind of massive change. </P> 
<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
